<div id="review_572419414" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/572419414" />
    <a title="Rebecca" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5649720-rebecca"><img alt="Rebecca" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1322357734p2/5649720.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/572419414?book_show_action=true">Mar 27, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Rebecca" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Rebecca" href="/user/show/5649720-rebecca">Rebecca</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5649720-rebecca?shelf=pop-science">pop-science</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer572419414" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14243355329204184596">Ever get stuck talking about the fairly pedestrian dreams of a random stranger, ad nauseum? Yeah, that&apos;s this book.<br/><br/>I&apos;ve read several of Sacks&apos; other books, which are usually good for both giving insight into how our minds work as well as scratching a certain voyeuristic itch. I&apos;m not entirely sure why this book fails at both--perhaps because we don&apos;t really understand enough about why we hallucinate. (Or perhaps the answer of &quot;neurons fire when they shouldn&apos;t have&quot; is just too simple and not all</span>
  <span id="freeText14243355329204184596" style="display:none">Ever get stuck talking about the fairly pedestrian dreams of a random stranger, ad nauseum? Yeah, that's this book.<br /><br />I've read several of Sacks' other books, which are usually good for both giving insight into how our minds work as well as scratching a certain voyeuristic itch. I'm not entirely sure why this book fails at both--perhaps because we don't really understand enough about why we hallucinate. (Or perhaps the answer of "neurons fire when they shouldn't have" is just too simple and not all that interesting.) <br /><br />The chapters are organized by type. We have hallucinations caused by phantom pain, by drugs, by Parkinsons, when falling asleep, etc. And they basically consist of lists: patient 1 saw zig zags, patient 2 saw random people in Victorian dress, patient 3 saw her dead cat. Nothing really about how this affected their lives or anything. Just "so and so saw x". <br /><br />Main conclusion: lots of things besides insanity cause people to see/hear/smell things. Many different things. That's about it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14243355329204184596" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


